where  is dimensionless, and we have also
scaled  and  into dimensionless
quantities. When we rotate the coordinates by  this becomes
the standard  action. This is a quite
universal model and besides the Yang-Mills theory it
relates e.g.  to the low energy limit of
(super)membranes. Despite its apparent simplicity
the  model has a number of remarkable
properties. Most notably, the
classical dynamics of () is chaotic which originally
led to a conjecture that the model is ergodic. This was proven to be
wrong by, who found that the phase space
of () admits a non-ergodic island consisting
of a periodic orbit surrounded by a stable, invariant torus
of classical solutions. Since
the quantum mechanical partition function is evaluated
by the Gutzwiller trace formula which sums
over all periodic solutions to Hamilton's equations,
these stable periodic orbits are clearly
pivotal to the quantization of (). In
fact, one could argue that if
() indeed does approximate the infrared limit of the
SU(2) Yang-Mills theory, the energies of these stable
periodic orbits are avatars of stable
glueball states in the Yang-Mills quantum theory.

