multiplicative redefinition of the action.

Note that the coupling constant flow ()
is like the flow of the one-loop coupling constant
in four dimensional Yang-Mills theory. In particular, in
the limit of small  the periodic classical solutions of
() exhibit asymptotically free self-similarity,
in the sense that in this limit () approaches
().

When we increase  we find an upper bound ,
where the renormalized coupling constant () diverges.
In the present case this Landau pole is physically relevant.
It determines a critical value of  which sets a
lower bound for the period , below which a periodic
orbit can not be extended by the self-similarity
transformation.

The Hamilton's equations of () can be readily solved
by numerical integrations. Previously it has been shownthat with  there is a periodic solution which is
surrounded by an stable, invariant torus formed by classical
solutions. Subsequently the existence of additional
periodic solutions with accompanying invariant torii
has been reported e.g.  in.
We have investigated the effects of a nonvanishing  in
() to the stability of the solution presented in.
When we increase  from 
while keeping the total energy of the
solution intact, we find that the torus of classical solutions
which surrounds the periodic orbit of retains its
invariant character for small values of the coupling .
But when the coupling approaches a critical value 
 we find that the torus looses its invariance properties
essentially by period doubling. This indicates that at 
the periodic orbit of looses its stability.

However, for non-vanishing  we also find novel 
periodic solutions with the physically interesting property
that their energies are negative, . Consequently
these solutions have an energy which is lower  than that
of the  ground state. These solutions are also
surrounded by stability islands which are formed by invariant
torii of  (not necessarily periodic) classical solutions.
Since  these stability islands consist of
trajectories which are entirely confined in one of the four
energy valleys which surround the minimum energy hyperbola
.
Consequently we can describe their properties by restricting
to one of the four valleys, and for definiteness we shall select the
valley where . We also employ the self-similar
