where instead of  the solutions are characterized by
some other distinguishing parameter. For this parameter
we choose the maximal value of  which is attainable to the
trajectory, say at . Notice that since the
energy is the sole conserved
quantity in (), the actual motion described by a
classical solution occurs in a three dimensional space.
Consequently we can visualize the trajectories in terms of
a three dimensional projection, and for this we select the
subspace . In particular, we can characterize
the trajectories using invariants of this three dimensional
space such as their self-linking number, provided the trajectories
are indeed linked.

